  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="preparation">          I&apos;d like to add a caveat to Paul Edward&apos;s story</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="20" relname="span"> -- an
          assignment involving human factors engineering may be a
          great way to inject some STS concerns into an otherwise
          socially unconcerned engineering course,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="21" relname="span"> BUT the discipline
          of human factors (or &quot;ergonomics,&quot; as the Europeans prefer)
          itself is a bit more compromised than that.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="15" relname="justify">

          I did my masters in human factors engineering at UCLA, and
          worked for a year in industry.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="13" relname="span">  At school it was certainly a
          more humane/politically interested group</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration"> (so much so that
          the dean tried to eliminate the department, claiming that
          that it was &quot;too empirical&quot; for the theoretical orientation
          of a University of Cal engineering school). </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="15" relname="span"> In terms of the
          professional society of human factors engineers, however,
          the majority of the money comes from military sources (even
          for disabled tech research),</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="concession"> and although the society
          newsletter occasionally prints letters with political/social
          criticism (e.g. protesting against the &quot;custer&apos;s revenge&quot;
          video game),</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="14" relname="span"> they are usually concerned more with trying to
          get conservative interests (industry-military)
          interested in hiring human factors engineers, and
          tend to shy away from any taint of social critique.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="17" relname="means">

          In becoming an STSer (or cyborg anthropologist or
          ethnomathematician or whatever the hell I am),</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="11" relname="antithesis"> I would have
          to say that I have not gained any more effective vantage
          point from which to effect the kinds of social change I&apos;d
          like to see,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="17" relname="span"> but rather have tied a different hand
          behind my back.</segment>
